{"type":"result","subtype":"success","is_error":false,"duration_ms":176090,"duration_api_ms":175778,"num_turns":3,"result":"Here's a summary of what the analysis found across the four agent definitions in `test-repos/.claude/agents/`:\n\n---\n\n**Structure — every file is identical in shape:**\n- 3-field YAML frontmatter: `name` (kebab-case, must match filename), `description` (single sentence, starts with action verb), `tools` (read-only only)\n- 4-section body: `Your Task` → `What to Read First` → Protocol/Checklist → `Output Format`\n- Length range: 48–66 lines\n\n**Tool discipline is strict:**\n- Only `Read`, `Grep`, `Glob` — never `Bash`, `Write`, or `Edit`\n- `plugin-structure-validator` intentionally omits `Glob` since it validates a single user-provided file rather than discovering files\n\n**Two output styles:**\n- **Checklist-with-verdict** (`plugin-structure-validator`, `migration-safety-reviewer`): `- [ ]` per check, then `PASS/FAIL/WARNING` verdict + corrected code snippets + blocking verdict (\"Safe to apply / Needs Changes / Block\")\n- **Numbered trace** (`chat-pipeline-analyzer`, `access-control-auditor`): narrative output with `file:line_number` references\n\n**Key gotchas baked into agent protocols:**\n- `BYPASS_ADMIN_ACCESS_CONTROL` defaults to `true` (silent over-permission for admins)\n- `request.state.direct` causes outlet filters to silently skip for API clients\n- SQLite requires `batch_alter_table` for any column alteration — missing it fails silently on PostgreSQL but breaks SQLite deployments\n- `?? true` fallbacks in permission code grant access when records are absent\n\n**Naming convention:** `<domain-noun>-<operation-noun>.md` — e.g. `migration-safety-reviewer.md`, `access-control-auditor.md`. The `name` frontmatter field must be the filename without `.md`.","stop_reason":"end_turn","session_id":"43f04cde-d072-4757-b99c-4d69efad515a","total_cost_usd":0.2723851,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":26238,"cache_read_input_tokens":73543,"output_tokens":5615,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":26238,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":1,"output_tokens":466,"cache_read_input_tokens":33878,"cache_creation_input_tokens":4422,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":4422},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"modelUsage":{"claude-sonnet-4-6":{"inputTokens":7,"outputTokens":5615,"cacheReadInputTokens":73543,"cacheCreationInputTokens":26238,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.20470139999999998,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000},"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001":{"inputTokens":20,"outputTokens":6427,"cacheReadInputTokens":57537,"cacheCreationInputTokens":23820,"webSearchRequests":0,"costUSD":0.0676837,"contextWindow":200000,"maxOutputTokens":32000}},"permission_denials":[],"structured_output":{"module_path":"test-repos/.claude/agents/","purpose":"Example subagent definition files used as test fixtures in ultrainit. They represent production-quality Claude Code subagent configurations for an open-webui codebase, covering four specialized read-only analysis workflows: chat pipeline tracing, plugin structure validation, Alembic migration safety review, and permission/access-control auditing. These fixtures demonstrate the expected output format that ultrainit's synthesis agent should generate.","architecture":{"overview":"Four standalone Markdown files, each defining one Claude Code subagent. Every file follows an identical four-section body layout (Your Task → What to Read First → Protocol/Checklist → Output Format) with YAML frontmatter (name, description, tools). Agents are purely read-only analytical tools — no Bash, Write, or Edit tools are granted. The directory is flat with no subdirectories.","subdirectories":[{"path":"test-repos/.claude/agents/","purpose":"Flat collection of four subagent Markdown definitions; no nesting. Each file is a self-contained agent specification.","key_files":["chat-pipeline-analyzer.md","plugin-structure-validator.md","migration-safety-reviewer.md","access-control-auditor.md"]}],"data_flow":"Each agent file is a static specification consumed by Claude Code at runtime. When a user invokes an agent (by name or trigger phrase), Claude Code reads the file, applies the frontmatter tool restrictions, and executes the body instructions against the target codebase. Agents read source files via Read/Grep/Glob and emit structured findings as text — they never write back to disk. In ultrainit's test suite, these fixtures are used to validate that the synthesis agent produces conformant subagent definitions."},"key_files":[{"path":"test-repos/.claude/agents/plugin-structure-validator.md","purpose":"Validates an open-webui plugin file for correct class structure, Valve definitions, method signatures, dunder parameters, event emitter usage, and security issues. The most detailed agent (66 lines, 7 checklist categories). Demonstrates the checklist-with-PASS/FAIL/WARNING output style.","importance":"critical"},{"path":"test-repos/.claude/agents/migration-safety-reviewer.md","purpose":"Reviews an Alembic migration file for SQLite compatibility, idempotency, column conventions, data migration safety, downgrade correctness, and access control convention adherence. Demonstrates corrected-code output style and explicit blocking verdict (Safe / Needs Changes / Block).","importance":"critical"},{"path":"test-repos/.claude/agents/access-control-auditor.md","purpose":"Audits effective user permissions by tracing group memberships, permission tree merging, and AccessGrant records. Unique in offering two protocols: narrow (specific route) and broad (full system). Demonstrates aggregated-findings output style.","importance":"critical"},{"path":"test-repos/.claude/agents/chat-pipeline-analyzer.md","purpose":"Traces a chat completion request through the open-webui FastAPI stack — middleware, filters, LLM dispatch, streaming. The shortest agent (52 lines); uses narrative trace output with file:line_number references rather than a checklist.","importance":"important"}],"patterns":[{"name":"Three-field YAML frontmatter","description":"Every agent file begins with exactly three YAML fields: `name` (kebab-case slug matching the filename without extension), `description` (single sentence starting with an action verb: Analyze/Validate/Review/Audit), and `tools` (CSV list restricted to read-only tools). No other frontmatter fields appear.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/chat-pipeline-analyzer.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/plugin-structure-validator.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/migration-safety-reviewer.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/access-control-auditor.md"]},{"name":"Four-section body layout","description":"All agents use the same four-section structure: (1) `## Your Task` — 1–2 sentences defining the mandate; (2) `## What to Read First` — numbered list of specific files with method/field hints; (3) a methodology section (`## Analysis Protocol`, `## Validation Checklist`, `## Review Checklist`, or `## Audit Protocol`) with detailed sub-steps; (4) `## Output Format` — numbered deliverables with explicit verdict criteria.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/plugin-structure-validator.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/migration-safety-reviewer.md"]},{"name":"Read-only tool discipline","description":"All agents restrict tools to `Read`, `Grep`, and/or `Glob`. No `Bash`, `Write`, or `Edit` tools appear anywhere. `Glob` is omitted from `plugin-structure-validator` because it validates a single user-provided file rather than discovering files across the codebase. Agents may show corrected code in their output text but cannot apply changes.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/plugin-structure-validator.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/access-control-auditor.md"]},{"name":"Checklist-with-verdict output (validation/review agents)","description":"Agents that assess correctness (`plugin-structure-validator`, `migration-safety-reviewer`) use `- [ ]` checkbox format for each check, then require a `PASS / FAIL / WARNING` verdict per item in the output, plus corrected code snippets for failures and a final blocking verdict (e.g. 'Safe to apply / Needs Changes / Block'). Trace agents (`chat-pipeline-analyzer`) use numbered narrative output instead.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/plugin-structure-validator.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/migration-safety-reviewer.md"]},{"name":"Domain-noun + operation-noun file naming","description":"Filenames follow `<domain>-<operation>.md` where domain describes the thing being analyzed (chat-pipeline, plugin-structure, migration-safety, access-control) and operation is an agentive noun (analyzer, validator, reviewer, auditor). All lowercase, kebab-case, no abbreviations.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/chat-pipeline-analyzer.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/access-control-auditor.md"]},{"name":"Specific file references in 'What to Read First'","description":"The second section names exact filenames with method or field hints (e.g. 'process_chat_payload() function', 'Valves field'). Agents list 4–5 files on average. This guides the agent to specific locations rather than broad exploration, reducing noise and token waste.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/chat-pipeline-analyzer.md","test-repos/.claude/agents/migration-safety-reviewer.md"]},{"name":"Dual-protocol design for variable scope","description":"access-control-auditor defines two sub-protocols under a single agent: 'For a specific route or resource' and 'For the full permission system'. This allows the same agent to handle both narrow (per-route) and comprehensive (all routes) audits without creating two separate agent files.","example_files":["test-repos/.claude/agents/access-control-auditor.md"]}],"conventions":{"naming":"Agent files: `<domain>-<operation>.md` in kebab-case (e.g. `migration-safety-reviewer.md`). The `name` field in frontmatter must exactly match the filename without `.md`. Description field always starts with a capitalized action verb (Analyze, Validate, Review, Audit) and ends with a period. Section headers use title case (`## Your Task`, `## What to Read First`, `## Output Format`).","imports":"No imports — these are Markdown specification files, not code. Tool declarations in frontmatter use comma-space-separated values matching Claude Code's exact tool names: `Read`, `Grep`, `Glob` (capitalized, no quotes).","error_handling":"Agents handle ambiguity through explicit verdict tiers rather than error states: PASS/FAIL/WARNING for checklist agents; 'Safe to apply / Needs Changes / Block' for migration agents; 'none/partial/full protection' for access-control agents. Silent failures are explicitly surfaced — chat-pipeline-analyzer has a dedicated 'Key Gotchas to Always Check' section listing stages that degrade silently without raising errors.","other":["Minimum agent length: ~48 lines (access-control-auditor). No agent exceeds 66 lines.","Checklist `- [ ]` format is used only in validation/review agents, not in trace agents.","Security flags are a required output element only in plugin-structure-validator, reflecting that plugin code is user-authored and untrusted.","Downgrade irreversibility must be explicitly commented in migration files — the agent checks for this and flags silent `pass` bodies.","All file references inside agent bodies point to the target codebase being analyzed, not to ultrainit's own files."]},"dependencies":{"internal":["tests/fixtures/ — these files serve as fixtures for ultrainit's bats-core test suite, validated by tests/scripts/validate_subagent.bats","scripts/validate-subagent.sh — the validation script checks that generated agents conform to the conventions demonstrated here","prompts/synthesizer-tooling.md — the synthesis agent prompt that must produce agents matching this format"],"external_key":[{"name":"Claude Code subagent runtime","purpose":"Consumes these Markdown files at invocation time; enforces the `tools` frontmatter restriction and routes user requests to the agent based on the `description` field's trigger phrases"},{"name":"open-webui codebase (test-repos/)","purpose":"The target codebase these agents are designed to analyze — all file references inside agent bodies (e.g. routers/openai.py, models/access_control.py) point into this repo"}]},"domain_terms":[{"term":"Valves","meaning":"A Pydantic model nested inside an open-webui plugin class that declares the plugin's configurable parameters. Must be defined inside the class body, not at module level."},{"term":"Dunder parameters","meaning":"Special `__` -prefixed method parameters in open-webui plugins (e.g. `__user__`, `__event_emitter__`) that are injected by the framework at runtime. Must be typed `Optional[...]` with a default of `None` for backward compatibility."},{"term":"batch_alter_table","meaning":"Alembic's SQLite-compatible wrapper for ALTER TABLE operations. Required for any column modification in SQLite because SQLite cannot natively alter columns. Migrations that skip this will fail on SQLite deployments."},{"term":"AccessGrant","meaning":"A database record in open-webui's permission system that grants a specific principal (user/group) access to a specific resource. Distinct from group memberships and feature gates."},{"term":"principal_id='*'","meaning":"A string literal asterisk (not NULL) used in AccessGrant records to denote a wildcard grant that applies to all principals. Easy to confuse with a NULL or absent value."},{"term":"BYPASS_ADMIN_ACCESS_CONTROL","meaning":"A config flag in open-webui that defaults to `true`, causing admins to bypass all per-resource AccessGrant checks. This is a common source of inadvertent over-permission."},{"term":"request.state.direct","meaning":"A Starlette request state flag set when a request comes from the API directly (not the UI). When true, outlet filters are skipped entirely — a silent behavioral difference not reflected in HTTP status codes."},{"term":"Manifold","meaning":"An open-webui plugin type that aggregates multiple models under a single plugin interface. Requires special ID parsing using `split('.', 1)` (split on first dot only) to extract the sub-model identifier."},{"term":"idempotency (migrations)","meaning":"The property that running a migration twice produces the same result as running it once. Achieved via guards like `get_existing_tables()` checks or `if_not_exists=True` flags on operations."},{"term":"N+1 query pattern","meaning":"An anti-pattern where a list endpoint calls `has_access()` per item in a loop rather than using the batch `get_accessible_resource_ids()` call. Flagged by access-control-auditor as a performance and correctness risk."}],"gotchas":[{"issue":"plugin-structure-validator omits `Glob` from its tools list, unlike the other three agents","solution":"This is intentional — it validates a single user-provided file and does not need filesystem discovery. Do not add Glob; the agent uses Grep for reference lookups in specific known files."},{"issue":"Agent `name` frontmatter field must exactly match the filename without `.md`; a mismatch causes Claude Code routing failures","solution":"When creating a new agent, derive the filename directly from the name field: `name: foo-bar-analyzer` → `foo-bar-analyzer.md`."},{"issue":"`BYPASS_ADMIN_ACCESS_CONTROL` defaults to `true` in open-webui, so admin users silently bypass all AccessGrant checks","solution":"access-control-auditor explicitly checks this flag first. When auditing admin-facing routes, always verify this default is intentional rather than assuming admins are subject to the same per-resource controls."},{"issue":"SQLite cannot perform `ALTER COLUMN` directly; migrations that omit `batch_alter_table` silently succeed on PostgreSQL but fail on SQLite","solution":"migration-safety-reviewer flags this as CRITICAL. Always use `with op.batch_alter_table('table_name') as batch_op:` for any column modification, even when only targeting PostgreSQL deployments."},{"issue":"outlet() in open-webui is not called for direct API requests (`request.state.direct == True`), making filter outlet logic silently inactive for API clients","solution":"chat-pipeline-analyzer surfaces this as a key gotcha. When adding outlet-side logic, verify whether it must also apply to direct API requests and handle the `direct` flag explicitly if so."},{"issue":"`?? true` permission fallbacks in access-control code silently grant access when a permission record is missing, rather than denying","solution":"access-control-auditor flags these as over-permission risks. Search for `?? true` in permission-evaluation code and verify each instance is intentional."},{"issue":"Checklist `- [ ]` format is a specification for the agent's internal tracking, not guaranteed to appear in the agent's final output — output format is defined separately in `## Output Format`","solution":"Do not confuse the methodology checklist (internal protocol) with the output format (what the user sees). The output section explicitly defines PASS/FAIL verdicts and corrected code snippets."},{"issue":"migration-safety-reviewer's `downgrade()` check requires an explicit comment when the operation is irreversible — a silent `pass` body is flagged as a WARNING even if technically correct","solution":"Add a comment like `# Irreversible: rows deleted in upgrade() cannot be restored` to any `pass` downgrade body."}],"commands":[{"command":"bash scripts/validate-subagent.sh test-repos/.claude/agents/plugin-structure-validator.md","purpose":"Validate that a subagent file conforms to ultrainit's expected frontmatter format, description trigger phrases, tool scoping, and minimum file reference count"}],"skill_opportunities":[{"name":"add-subagent","description":"Scaffold a new subagent definition file following the exact conventions demonstrated in these fixtures: three-field frontmatter, four-section body, read-only tools, checklist or trace output style, domain-noun + operation-noun filename","workflow_steps":["Prompt user for agent name (kebab-case), one-sentence description, and target domain","Determine output style: checklist-with-verdict (validation/review) or numbered-trace (analysis)","Select appropriate tools: Read + Grep + Glob for file-discovery agents; Read + Grep only for single-file validators","Generate the four-section body with placeholder file references and checklist items","Run scripts/validate-subagent.sh on the generated file and fix any issues","Write to .claude/agents/<name>.md"]},{"name":"audit-subagent-quality","description":"Run validate-subagent.sh across all files in .claude/agents/ and report which agents fail frontmatter, tool-scoping, file-reference, or description-trigger checks","workflow_steps":["Glob .claude/agents/*.md to collect all agent files","Run scripts/validate-subagent.sh on each file","Aggregate PASS/FAIL results into a summary table","For each failure, show the specific check that failed and the required fix"]}]},"terminal_reason":"completed","fast_mode_state":"off","uuid":"51cac1cd-c1ce-44dd-aafd-b165c073897d"}
